  "prompt": "What is the difference between a beta particle and an electron?",
  "response": "While beta particles and electrons are fundamentally the same particle, the distinction lies in their origin and how they are produced:\n\n*   **Electron:** This is a fundamental particle that exists independently or as a component of an atom, orbiting the nucleus. Electrons are involved in chemical bonding and electrical conductivity.\n\n*   **Beta Particle:** This is an electron (or its antiparticle, a positron) that is emitted during radioactive decay from the nucleus of an atom. This occurs when a neutron in the nucleus transforms into a proton, emitting an electron (beta-minus decay), or when a proton transforms into a neutron, emitting a positron (beta-plus decay).\n\nIn essence:\n\n*   An electron is a general term for the particle orbiting the nucleus.\n*   A beta particle is an electron (or positron) specifically ejected from the nucleus during radioactive decay.\n\nTherefore, all beta particles are electrons (or positrons), but not all electrons are beta particles. An electron becomes a beta particle when it originates from the nucleus during radioactive decay.",
